Step 1. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
• Definition: (Main Business Revenue) / (Accounts Receivable)  
• Here, Main Business Revenue = 7,825,951.24  
  Accounts Receivable (End Amount) = 1,988,616.02  
• Calculation: 7,825,951.24 / 1,988,616.02 ≈ 3.93  

Step 2. Operating Cash Flow Ratio and Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio  
• Both ratios use Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities divided by Total Current Liabilities.  
• Here, Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –4,398,760.38  
  Total Current Liabilities = 2,491,297.55  
• Calculation: –4,398,760.38 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ –1.77  
• (Thus, both the “operating cash flow ratio” and the “operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio” equal –1.77.)  

Step 3. Total Asset Turnover Ratio  
• Definition: (Total Revenue) / (Total Assets)  
• Here, Total Revenue = 7,825,951.24  
  Total Assets (End Amount) = 14,089,860.66  
• Calculation: 7,825,951.24 / 14,089,860.66 ≈ 0.56  

Step 4. Debt to Equity Ratio  
• Definition: (Total Liabilities) / (Owner’s Equity)  
• Here, Total Liabilities can be derived as:  
  Total Liabilities = Total Liabilities and Owner’s Equity – Total Owner’s Equity  
  = 14,089,860.66 – 11,598,563.11  
  = 2,491,297.55  
  Owner’s Equity = 11,598,563.11  
• Calculation: 2,491,297.55 / 11,598,563.11 ≈ 0.21  

Thus, the answer is:

    "operating cash flow ratio": "-1.77",
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-1.77",
    "Total Asset Turnover Ratio": "0.56",
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.21"
  }
}
